	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />It's fairly easy to generate the 32ksample loop that the NES's noise channel uses. The following C code will generate it on stdout (8bits/sample, 1 channel)
<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">int main &#40;int argc, char * argv&#91;&#93;&#41; &#123;<br />&nbsp; unsigned char feedback;<br />&nbsp; unsigned short nreg=1;<br />&nbsp; int i;<br /><br />&nbsp; for &#40;i=0;i&lt;32767;i++&#41; &#123;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; feedback=&#40;&#40;nreg&gt;&gt;13&#41;&amp;1&#41;^&#40;&#40;nreg&gt;&gt;14&#41;&amp;1&#41;;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; nreg=&#40;nreg&lt;&lt;1&#41;+feedback;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; nreg&amp;=0x7FFF;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; putchar&#40;&#40;&#40;nreg&gt;&gt;14&#41;&amp;1&#41;?'~':' '&#41;;<br />&nbsp; &#125;<br />&#125;</div>
<br />
<br />Then you loop it and only play it at specific sample rates, specifically (for US NESes) 3,579,545 Hz divided by the numbers in the NTSC line at <a href="http://nesdevwiki.org/wiki/APU_Noise" class="postlink">http://nesdevwiki.org/wiki/APU_Noise</a>
<br />
<br />For the NES triangle, just take an ordinary triangle wave and degrade it to 4bits.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


